WEBVTT

00:06.923 --> 00:10.260
(slow orchestral music)

00:32.365 --> 00:35.869
(airplane engines roaring)

00:38.705 --> 00:42.876
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:34.552 --> 01:38.723
(slow orchestral
music continues)

02:21.266 --> 02:23.768
(traffic roars)

02:30.942 --> 02:35.280
(slow orchestral
music continues)

02:46.791 --> 02:49.627
(Kiki sighs)

02:49.627 --> 02:53.798
(slow orchestral
music continues)

03:04.100 --> 03:07.061
(doorbell buzzes)

03:16.821 --> 03:19.824
(slow piano music)

03:51.022 --> 03:52.565
How long do they say he has?

03:54.359 --> 03:56.569
A day, two.

03:57.904 --> 03:58.738
Could be any time.

04:06.704 --> 04:08.373
Do you think he can hear us?

04:08.373 --> 04:11.209
I don't think so, though,

04:13.378 --> 04:15.546
I think he hears music.

04:15.546 --> 04:18.216
He'll squeeze my hand sometimes

04:18.216 --> 04:21.177
when I put on Bach or
his favorite Beethoven.

04:27.725 --> 04:32.730
I'm glad you came, Kiki.
(slow orchestral music)

04:34.357 --> 04:35.233
Me too.

04:37.193 --> 04:38.194
How's your mother?

04:43.700 --> 04:44.575
Sad.

04:47.745 --> 04:48.746
And Chuck?

04:50.415 --> 04:51.416
Sad too, I think.

04:57.088 --> 04:59.215
Well, how long has it been?

04:59.215 --> 05:00.258
Since their divorce?

05:00.258 --> 05:03.428
No, since we last visited you,

05:03.428 --> 05:04.929
or, rather, since Michael did.

05:08.433 --> 05:10.435
- It had to be at
least five years ago,

05:11.602 --> 05:13.104
right before Dad left Mom.

05:14.439 --> 05:18.609
(slow orchestral
music continues)

05:20.278 --> 05:21.237
And how's Alan?

05:24.949 --> 05:29.120
- He's good, he's on
tour in Australia.

05:29.120 --> 05:30.455
He'll be gone for a while.

05:33.291 --> 05:35.084
What's for a while?

05:36.627 --> 05:40.465
- Six, seven weeks, maybe
longer if they sell out.

05:40.465 --> 05:43.134
Oh, that's a long time.

05:45.970 --> 05:46.637
I know.

05:59.275 --> 06:00.151
I'm,

06:01.652 --> 06:04.322
I'm so sorry we lost touch
these past few years.

06:07.283 --> 06:08.326
Earl died, you know?

06:09.160 --> 06:10.661
We heard.

06:10.661 --> 06:11.496
In a bar fight.

06:12.497 --> 06:13.623
(both laughing)

06:13.623 --> 06:14.665
That I didn't know.

06:17.335 --> 06:20.338
He could never stay away
from the John Barleycorn,

06:20.338 --> 06:21.172
as he put it.

06:23.299 --> 06:25.676
But he sure could fly a plane.

06:25.676 --> 06:26.511
That he could.

06:28.679 --> 06:30.348
Michael was never happier

06:30.348 --> 06:32.350
than when he was up
in the air with him.

06:35.478 --> 06:37.688
I don't think I ever
saw Michael happier

06:37.688 --> 06:40.483
than the day he came home

06:40.483 --> 06:43.653
from making his first
perfect landing.

06:43.653 --> 06:46.697
(Kiki laughs)

06:46.697 --> 06:48.032
Seems a lifetime ago.

06:50.159 --> 06:53.037
(slow piano music)

06:54.038 --> 06:57.333
(slow orchestral music)

07:03.381 --> 07:06.884
(airplane engine rumbles)

07:06.884 --> 07:08.845
- [Earl] I could
go for some coffee.

07:08.845 --> 07:10.721
- [Michael] I just
made what is probably

07:10.721 --> 07:14.392
the most perfect landing
this old tub has ever seen,

07:14.392 --> 07:16.561
and that's all that you can say?

07:16.561 --> 07:19.564
- [Earl] Well, maybe
a big piece of pie.

07:19.564 --> 07:21.899
- Okay, now, I know
what I did wrong.

07:21.899 --> 07:24.402
Let's go back up, I
want to get it right.

07:24.402 --> 07:25.570
You got it right.

07:25.570 --> 07:27.405
I want to get it perfect.

07:27.405 --> 07:28.865
(Earl laughs)

07:28.865 --> 07:32.368
- Perfect, (laughs) he
wants to get it perfect.

07:33.578 --> 07:36.247
Listen, you can practice
all the landings

07:36.247 --> 07:38.416
you want on your solo.

07:38.416 --> 07:39.584
Solo?

07:45.756 --> 07:47.258
It was perfect, wasn't it?

07:48.593 --> 07:50.261
- Yeah, I think maybe
I'll have a couple

07:50.261 --> 07:54.724
of big scoops of ice
cream, too. (laughs)

07:58.102 --> 08:01.439
(slow orchestral music)

08:18.456 --> 08:20.791
(slow music)

09:04.627 --> 09:06.170
Mount Samsonite.

09:06.170 --> 09:08.339
- We're only gonna
be gone a week.

09:08.339 --> 09:10.508
- Well, we could take the kids
or we could take the luggage.

09:10.508 --> 09:13.636
Hmm, take the kids.

09:13.636 --> 09:15.513
Good choice. (laughs)

09:15.513 --> 09:17.348
Jan, these parents
think you're a genius

09:17.348 --> 09:18.516
for getting the kids
out of the house

09:18.516 --> 09:20.309
during spring vacation.

09:20.309 --> 09:22.186
- It's not the choir
tour that's doing it.

09:22.186 --> 09:24.814
It's the two days of skiing
we dangled in front of them.

09:24.814 --> 09:26.482
Oh, you're being modest.

09:26.482 --> 09:27.858
I mean, we've never
had a choir director

09:27.858 --> 09:29.860
to get these kids to
sound so fantastic.

09:29.860 --> 09:32.488
- I tell them Bruce Springsteen
got his start singing

09:32.488 --> 09:33.531
in a church choir.

09:34.532 --> 09:36.200
He did, didn't he?

09:36.200 --> 09:38.536
(Jan laughs)

09:40.371 --> 09:41.706
Sweetie, what are you doing?

09:41.706 --> 09:43.374
Kicking the tires.

09:43.374 --> 09:44.875
Any particular reason?

09:44.875 --> 09:47.878
- Daddy always does it
before we take a trip.

09:47.878 --> 09:50.881
- Oh, we're gonna
miss him, aren't we?

09:52.550 --> 09:54.552
I'm worried about Daddy.

09:54.552 --> 09:57.221
A whole week, he
could starve to death.

09:57.221 --> 09:58.723
(Jan laughs)

09:58.723 --> 10:00.725
- Why don't we go
give him a call?

10:00.725 --> 10:03.394
- Okay.
- Okay, (laughs) come on.

10:03.394 --> 10:05.521
(overlapping chattering)
(slow country music)

10:05.521 --> 10:09.358
- That's fine.
(overlapping chattering)

10:12.570 --> 10:13.571
Would you like some coffee?

10:13.571 --> 10:15.239
Oh, no, thanks.

10:15.239 --> 10:18.409
- Well, at least he
didn't auger us in.

10:18.409 --> 10:20.369
Airplane's all in one piece,

10:20.369 --> 10:22.580
but the landing gear does look
a little like a squashed bug.

10:22.580 --> 10:24.415
- Like a bug, huh?
- Oh, what do you mean?

10:24.415 --> 10:25.750
It was perfect, you know,
I could have walked out

10:25.750 --> 10:27.376
on the wing and watched.

10:28.419 --> 10:30.379
It would have landed itself.

10:30.379 --> 10:32.048
- Mm-hmm, you let me know
before you do that, okay?

10:32.048 --> 10:33.716
- Well, that crosswind
didn't seem to bother you.

10:33.716 --> 10:35.593
Oh, no, don't let it fool you.

10:35.593 --> 10:36.927
There was six knots of
crosswind out there, huh?

10:38.763 --> 10:40.264
Did you see me land?

10:40.264 --> 10:41.766
- [Chuck] It looked good from-

10:41.766 --> 10:42.099
- You see, he said
it was perfect.

10:43.893 --> 10:45.936
- Any landing he can walk
away from is perfect.

10:45.936 --> 10:47.938
- Oh, yeah, oops.
(phone beeps)

10:47.938 --> 10:49.732
A phone call, a
phone call, here.

10:49.732 --> 10:51.776
You guys see that
strong front up north?

10:51.776 --> 10:53.778
- No.
- What, north of here?

10:53.778 --> 10:55.946
- Yeah, it looked hung
up over the mountains.

10:55.946 --> 10:57.615
It'll bring a little
precip, though.

10:57.615 --> 10:59.450
You weather boys better
keep an eye out, now.

10:59.450 --> 11:02.787
- Hey, look at this guy,
he's dropping like an anvil.

11:03.913 --> 11:05.790
[Earl] Like on a pogo stick.

11:05.790 --> 11:07.750
- Yeah, he's going up and
down and up and down and up

11:09.293 --> 11:11.087
- and down and up and down.
- You watch,

11:11.087 --> 11:13.589
next thing you know, he'll be
in here, bragging about it.

11:13.589 --> 11:14.965
You're darn right, yeah.

11:16.634 --> 11:17.635
I'll see you later, Chuck.

11:17.635 --> 11:18.594
[Chuck] You bet.

11:20.638 --> 11:21.639
That's good pie.

11:23.432 --> 11:26.602
- Come along, Yeager,
we gotta go to work.

11:26.602 --> 11:28.979
- Oh, I just want to sit here
and think about that landing.

11:28.979 --> 11:33.776
- [Earl] Yeah, well,
knock yourself out.

11:33.776 --> 11:37.655
- You know, it was perfect,
it was absolutely perfect.

11:40.449 --> 11:41.992
- Daddy, can Jennifer
spend the weekend

11:41.992 --> 11:43.994
with us when we get back?

11:43.994 --> 11:46.497
- Well, I don't mind if
it's okay with Mommy.

11:46.497 --> 11:47.665
It's okay with Mommy.

11:50.000 --> 11:52.837
Jennifer's mommy
moved away last week.

11:52.837 --> 11:55.798
Her dad's not home
much of the time.

11:55.798 --> 11:58.509
Oh, all right, well, we'll,

11:58.509 --> 12:01.011
we'll do something fun, okay?

12:01.011 --> 12:02.638
- Okay, I love you,
Daddy. (kisses)

12:02.638 --> 12:04.181
- [Chuck] I love
you, too, pumpkin.

12:04.181 --> 12:05.850
Here's Mommy again.

12:07.685 --> 12:09.520
Chuck, the bus is packed,

12:09.520 --> 12:11.480
so they're loading the sound
equipment in the Blazer.

12:11.480 --> 12:13.649
- [Chuck] Oh, well, I guess
you'll have to take it.

12:13.649 --> 12:16.694
Listen, uh, tell Dennis
that there's a chance

12:16.694 --> 12:19.196
of snow at about 9,000
feet in the mountains.

12:19.196 --> 12:21.699
- [Jan] I will, I gotta run,
the caravan's pulling out.

12:21.699 --> 12:23.534
Talk to you soon.
(slow orchestral music)

12:23.534 --> 12:24.702
- Honey, you know, maybe
it wouldn't be a bad idea

12:24.702 --> 12:26.162
to wait until in the morning,

12:26.162 --> 12:27.997
just to see what that
storm's gonna do.

12:27.997 --> 12:29.707
- We'd have to cancel
our first concert.

12:29.707 --> 12:31.876
Everything will be
just fine, Chuck.

12:31.876 --> 12:34.044
The show must go on, remember?

12:34.044 --> 12:35.379
I'll call you tomorrow.

12:35.379 --> 12:36.172
[Chuck] Honey.

12:36.172 --> 12:38.048
What?

12:38.048 --> 12:41.677
- Um, well, nothing, just,
well, (stammer) good luck.

12:41.677 --> 12:43.387
(Chuck laughs)

12:43.387 --> 12:45.514
And break your legs, or
whatever that is they say, okay?

12:46.223 --> 12:47.558
Drive safely.

12:47.558 --> 12:50.561
Bye, love you. (kisses)

12:51.896 --> 12:54.565
(wind whistles)

12:55.900 --> 12:56.734
I'm hungry.

12:56.734 --> 12:57.902
Alan!

12:57.902 --> 12:59.570
- We thought you
were on the bus.

12:59.570 --> 13:01.739
- With all those little
Twinkies, yippee.

13:01.739 --> 13:03.240
We're gonna have fun.

13:03.240 --> 13:04.909
- You know it, how's
my girlfriend doing?

13:04.909 --> 13:06.744
(Kiki giggles)

13:06.744 --> 13:08.579
- [Jan] You don't want to
ride with the other kids?

13:08.579 --> 13:10.414
- Look, I don't mind
doing the sound and stuff,

13:10.414 --> 13:12.082
and sometimes their
singing doesn't want

13:12.082 --> 13:13.918
to make me throw up too bad,

13:13.918 --> 13:16.921
but I'm not gonna hang out
with those (indistinct).

13:16.921 --> 13:18.756
Ooh, what's that?

13:18.756 --> 13:20.758
- You like it,
pretty gnarly, huh?

13:20.758 --> 13:21.926
It's geeky looking.

13:21.926 --> 13:23.761
You don't like it?

13:23.761 --> 13:25.262
Does this mean you're not
my girlfriend anymore?

13:25.262 --> 13:26.597
I guess not. (laughs)

13:26.597 --> 13:27.765
I guess not.

13:28.766 --> 13:30.100
Mommy, did you see this?

13:31.936 --> 13:34.438
- It's, it's a very
pretty earring.

13:35.606 --> 13:37.107
(car engine revs)

13:37.107 --> 13:41.570
- [Children] Bye!
(children screaming)

13:46.617 --> 13:49.954
(slow orchestral music)

14:28.826 --> 14:33.831
(slow violin music)
(slow orchestral music)

15:34.725 --> 15:39.229
Bravo. (cheers)

15:39.229 --> 15:41.231
No, (laughs) it was terrible.

15:41.231 --> 15:44.902
(Michael whistles)

15:44.902 --> 15:46.236
(Michael cheers)

15:46.236 --> 15:47.738
That was great.

15:48.739 --> 15:50.240
[Laura] It was terrible.

15:50.240 --> 15:51.408
- It's incredible,
I can't believe

15:51.408 --> 15:52.409
you still remember that piece.

15:52.409 --> 15:53.911
Only every third bar.

15:53.911 --> 15:55.746
- How'd this happen,
huh, my darling.

15:57.915 --> 15:59.917
I just felt like playing.

15:59.917 --> 16:01.377
- Ah, and it felt-

16:01.377 --> 16:03.712
- It felt good.
- It felt good.

16:03.712 --> 16:08.384
Ooh, it felt good.
(Laura laughs)

16:08.384 --> 16:10.761
- I shouldn't have tried
the Tchaikovsky, though.

16:10.761 --> 16:12.262
It was too ambitious.

16:12.262 --> 16:13.764
- Oh, but darling,
it was beautiful.

16:13.764 --> 16:15.265
- Yes?
- It was very, very beautiful.

16:15.265 --> 16:16.433
I even had tears in my eyes.

16:16.433 --> 16:18.060
I don't believe you, no.

16:18.060 --> 16:19.770
- Yes, I did, I
cried over there,

16:19.770 --> 16:21.105
- I never showed you my-
- You're in such a good mood.

16:21.105 --> 16:22.106
What happened to you today?

16:22.106 --> 16:23.273
What do you mean?

16:23.273 --> 16:24.441
Huh, yeah, what happened?

16:24.441 --> 16:26.110
Why, what do you mean?

16:26.110 --> 16:27.236
- 'Cause you're in
such a good mood.

16:27.236 --> 16:29.446
I made aviation history!

16:29.446 --> 16:33.075
I made a perfect
landing. (laughs)

16:33.075 --> 16:35.119
It was perfect, it was perfect.

16:35.119 --> 16:36.286
[Laura] Really perfect, huh?

16:36.286 --> 16:37.955
It was incredible. (laughs)

16:37.955 --> 16:41.750
And I, oh, and I drove
Earl crazy. (sings)

16:41.750 --> 16:44.795
Listen to this, I
kept humming. (sings)

16:46.130 --> 16:47.798
(slow piano music)

16:47.798 --> 16:57.141
♪ I just made a
perfect landing ♪

16:57.141 --> 16:58.809
♪ I just most a
perfect landing ♪

16:58.809 --> 17:05.149
♪ I just made a
perfect landing ♪

17:05.149 --> 17:06.817
♪ I just made a perfect landing,
made a perfect landing ♪

17:06.817 --> 17:09.945
♪ I just made a
perfect landing ♪

17:09.945 --> 17:11.989
♪ I've just made a
perfect landing ♪

17:11.989 --> 17:12.990
Huh?

17:12.990 --> 17:15.159
Bravo, (claps) bravo!

17:15.159 --> 17:16.785
- Oh, where are
the (indistinct)?

17:16.785 --> 17:18.829
Was it, uh, really perfect?

17:18.829 --> 17:23.292
- It, (stammers)
well, it was good.

17:25.002 --> 17:27.463
It was very good and
it was beautiful.

17:27.463 --> 17:28.338
I love it.

17:29.965 --> 17:31.842
You don't know what
it's like up there.

17:35.345 --> 17:38.307
Really, I have to get
you up there, you okay?

17:41.018 --> 17:42.811
Yeah, just a chill.

17:46.857 --> 17:48.859
We haven't had too
many good days.

17:50.027 --> 17:51.028
We've got this one.

17:52.821 --> 17:53.822
Hold that thought.

18:01.705 --> 18:03.999
He was so happy that day.

18:06.043 --> 18:09.505
You'd think he'd flown to
the moon and back. (sighs)

18:12.216 --> 18:16.345
Seems like he spent every
spare minute he had up there

18:16.345 --> 18:18.555
in the air with Earl.

18:18.555 --> 18:20.891
(slow piano music)

18:20.891 --> 18:22.893
Used to fly with
Chuck, too, remember?

18:24.561 --> 18:27.731
- No, but the one
thing I do remember is

18:27.731 --> 18:32.361
that I had this little girl
crush on Alan. (laughs)

18:33.403 --> 18:35.197
And that Aussie accent.

18:35.197 --> 18:36.073
Oh.

18:37.199 --> 18:38.575
(both laughing)

18:38.575 --> 18:40.577
- We married a
couple of charmers.

18:40.577 --> 18:41.411
We did.

18:43.747 --> 18:45.916
- You still have no
memory of that night?

18:48.085 --> 18:50.254
No, but the doctors say

18:50.254 --> 18:54.091
that it's not that
unusual. (laughs)

18:55.551 --> 18:57.427
What, (laughs) what?

18:57.427 --> 19:00.931
- The only thing that I remember
is those silly little songs

19:00.931 --> 19:02.099
we used to sing, like.

19:03.433 --> 19:06.937
♪ There is a hole in
the bottom of the sea ♪

19:06.937 --> 19:08.939
Or.

19:08.939 --> 19:11.233
♪ Row, row, row your boat
gently down the stream ♪

19:11.233 --> 19:12.943
♪ Merrily, merrily,
merrily, merrily ♪

19:12.943 --> 19:14.444
♪ Life is but a dream

19:14.444 --> 19:17.281
(both laughing)

19:18.282 --> 19:19.616
It seems a lifetime ago.

19:20.784 --> 19:24.454
(slow piano music continues)

19:36.967 --> 19:38.969
- You know, Dad never
did forgive her.

19:40.470 --> 19:42.139
Forgive her for what?

19:42.139 --> 19:43.265
[Kiki] The accident.

19:45.601 --> 19:47.311
- The accident
wasn't Jan's fault.

19:49.146 --> 19:51.315
- Mom said that she
never even saw it coming.

19:54.818 --> 19:55.611
We rarely do,

19:58.989 --> 20:01.491
see the danger, that
is, until it's too late.

20:09.499 --> 20:12.169
- Hmm, ooh, I've
gotta go, I'm late.

20:12.169 --> 20:14.171
- Uh, do you want me to cook
you some eggs or something?

20:14.171 --> 20:15.505
Yeah, that'd be great.

20:15.505 --> 20:17.174
You know, I just didn't
say it was perfect.

20:17.174 --> 20:18.342
Chuck Scott said it
was perfect, too.

20:18.342 --> 20:19.843
Who's Chuck Scott? (laughs)

20:19.843 --> 20:21.345
- He's a guy who
works at the airport.

20:21.345 --> 20:23.180
- Oh, hey, by the
way, do you know

20:23.180 --> 20:24.640
what happened to the money
I left on the mantel?

20:24.640 --> 20:26.516
- Yeah, I paid her
off with the airplane,

20:26.516 --> 20:29.311
the gas and the oil, stuff
like that, you know, why?

20:29.311 --> 20:31.021
It was $40 there. (laughs)

20:31.021 --> 20:32.981
Well, I'll pay you back.

20:32.981 --> 20:35.025
[Laura] It's not important.

20:35.025 --> 20:37.027
I said I'd pay you back.

20:37.027 --> 20:38.528
- Look, I was just
going shopping

20:38.528 --> 20:40.030
and I thought maybe I'd
lost it or something-

20:40.030 --> 20:42.866
- I get paid on Fridays,
that soon enough?

20:42.866 --> 20:44.201
Mike, please.

20:44.201 --> 20:45.369
I gotta go, it's late.

20:47.204 --> 20:48.664
- It'll just take a minute
to cook you an omelet.

20:48.664 --> 20:50.332
- [Michael] No, I
gotta get dressed.

20:50.332 --> 20:52.209
I'm late, and I'm
not hungry anyway.

20:52.209 --> 20:55.545
(slow orchestral music)

20:59.508 --> 21:03.220
(slow orchestral music)

21:03.220 --> 21:05.180
♪ There are a log

21:05.180 --> 21:07.557
♪ There's a log in the hole
in the bottom of the sea ♪

21:07.557 --> 21:09.226
♪ There's a log in the hole

21:09.226 --> 21:11.561
♪ In the bottom of the sea

21:11.561 --> 21:15.691
(slow orchestral
music continues)

21:17.234 --> 21:21.571
(children squealing)
(overlapping chattering)

21:23.240 --> 21:26.702
♪ And crown thy good
with brotherhood ♪

21:26.702 --> 21:30.247
♪ From sea to shining sea

21:31.373 --> 21:32.416
(group laughs)

21:32.416 --> 21:34.084
Come on, Alan, sing with us.

21:34.084 --> 21:35.210
No, that's okay.

21:35.210 --> 21:36.586
[Jan] Oh, come on, it's fun.

21:36.586 --> 21:38.922
- Nobody really believes
that God and motherhood

21:38.922 --> 21:41.216
and apple pie stuff,
one push of a button,

21:41.216 --> 21:44.094
and the whole world's
gonna get blown to bits.

21:44.094 --> 21:48.056
- Oh, no, God would never
let anybody do that.

21:48.056 --> 21:51.601
♪ Row, row, row your boat
gently down the stream ♪

21:51.601 --> 21:53.562
♪ Merrily, merrily,
merrily, merrily ♪

21:53.562 --> 21:55.605
♪ Life is but a dream

21:55.605 --> 21:59.109
(wind whistles)

21:59.109 --> 22:01.069
- [Michael] Can we really
make money that way?

22:01.069 --> 22:04.614
- Hey, there are some big
bucks to be made, my friend.

22:04.614 --> 22:07.117
Look, all we have to do
is fly these jokers up

22:07.117 --> 22:09.953
into the mountains, they
hunt, fish, backpack,

22:09.953 --> 22:11.955
watch the birdies, whatever.

22:11.955 --> 22:14.624
A week later, we go back
and pick them up, easy.

22:14.624 --> 22:16.293
But is there any money in it?

22:16.293 --> 22:18.795
- Look, all we have
to do is advertise

22:18.795 --> 22:20.630
in the big newspapers back east,

22:20.630 --> 22:24.301
we've got more business than
we can handle, I promise you.

22:24.301 --> 22:25.802
(patient moans)

22:25.802 --> 22:27.637
Take it easy, buddy,
it's just a leg.

22:27.637 --> 22:30.640
(Michael whistles)

22:34.311 --> 22:35.979
Where's Dr. Mick?

22:35.979 --> 22:37.481
He told me not to wake him

22:37.481 --> 22:38.815
for anything less than
a heart transplant.

22:38.815 --> 22:40.484
If we use him as a donor,

22:40.484 --> 22:41.777
then we wouldn't have
to wake him, would we?

22:41.777 --> 22:44.654
(secretary laughs)

22:49.993 --> 22:52.829
(Michael whistles)

22:58.126 --> 23:01.505
- Dietrich, you have no
respect for the dead.

23:02.798 --> 23:07.677
♪ We have got another
skier special ♪

23:07.677 --> 23:10.347
- Is it tibia,
fibular, or femur?

23:11.681 --> 23:12.682
[Michael] Femur.

23:12.682 --> 23:14.184
Trauma to the knee?

23:15.519 --> 23:17.020
Not evident.

23:17.020 --> 23:18.688
Hypothermia?

23:18.688 --> 23:19.523
[Michael] Nope.

23:21.149 --> 23:22.651
- Well, I don't know
what it was like

23:22.651 --> 23:24.194
when you were in medical school,

23:24.194 --> 23:26.696
but by the time I
finished my second year,

23:26.696 --> 23:28.865
I could set a simple
closed fracture

23:28.865 --> 23:31.034
with my hands behind my back.

23:32.494 --> 23:33.703
- And what is that
supposed to mean?

23:36.373 --> 23:40.502
- I just happened to be going
through some personnel files.

23:43.380 --> 23:47.717
You completed two years at
Columbia Medical School.

23:47.717 --> 23:50.554
(slow piano music)

23:54.516 --> 23:57.394
That was a long time ago.

23:57.394 --> 23:59.396
I was just curious

23:59.396 --> 24:03.233
as to why a capable young
man like you would want

24:03.233 --> 24:06.403
to work in a small
town clinic like this.

24:06.403 --> 24:10.240
(slow piano music continues)

24:12.576 --> 24:15.203
- I thought the personnel
files were confidential,

24:15.203 --> 24:17.581
you know, between me and
the personnel department.

24:19.541 --> 24:20.917
- Yeah, well, it is, yes,
it is, it certainly is.

24:25.213 --> 24:28.592
But Dietrich, I am the
personnel department.

24:28.592 --> 24:29.759
[Michael] Oh!

24:31.595 --> 24:36.099
- Oh, all right, all
right, I'm coming. (sighs)

24:37.225 --> 24:40.437
(slow piano music continues)

24:43.440 --> 24:46.776
(slow orchestral music)

24:51.239 --> 24:52.616
(slow piano music)

24:52.616 --> 24:53.241
You were ranked
seventh in your class,

24:54.784 --> 24:57.454
started missing lectures,
did poorly on exams,

24:57.454 --> 24:59.122
and eventually, you quit.

25:03.293 --> 25:04.628
- Don't let him
bother you, Mike.

25:04.628 --> 25:06.421
He's always bothering me.

25:06.421 --> 25:08.298
- Well, you know, he's
always getting involved

25:08.298 --> 25:12.135
with things that, you know,
just are none of his business.

25:15.639 --> 25:20.644
And, uh, someday I
just, you know, (sighs)

25:23.271 --> 25:25.482
well, I think I'll
go home and eat.

25:25.482 --> 25:29.319
(slow piano music continues)

25:37.661 --> 25:41.331
(ominous orchestral music)

26:21.037 --> 26:24.541
(glass shatters)

26:24.541 --> 26:28.878
(ominous orchestral
music continues)

26:37.721 --> 26:38.888
[Jan] Oh my God, Kiki?

26:41.516 --> 26:42.559
Oh, Alan!

26:42.559 --> 26:43.893
[Alan] What happened?

26:43.893 --> 26:46.021
[Jan] Oh, Kiki!

26:46.021 --> 26:49.357
(door creaks)

26:49.357 --> 26:51.901
(fire crackles)

27:08.251 --> 27:10.754
(Michael sings)

27:15.759 --> 27:18.428
(fire crackles)

27:36.613 --> 27:39.616
(slow piano music)

28:03.973 --> 28:08.978
♪ Forgive me, again,
if I offended ♪

28:10.605 --> 28:15.110
♪ And turned something
right into up and dead ♪

28:16.653 --> 28:21.658
♪ Modeled what
was comprehended ♪

28:23.326 --> 28:26.996
♪ But the 15th time will
be a different thing ♪

28:28.998 --> 28:34.003
♪ Forgive me, I know
how I've been foolish ♪

28:35.672 --> 28:40.468
♪ And turned something
hot into coolish ♪

28:41.803 --> 28:46.516
♪ I was so childish
and cruel-ish ♪

28:47.851 --> 28:51.855
♪ But the 15th time will
be a different thing ♪

28:53.857 --> 28:57.485
♪ I'm ashamed, I'm ashamed

28:57.485 --> 29:00.363
♪ I'm a louse, I'm a louse

29:00.363 --> 29:03.867
♪ I can't believe some
of the things that I do ♪

29:03.867 --> 29:06.703
♪ Not just to you

29:06.703 --> 29:09.706
♪ Do you think just once more

29:09.706 --> 29:13.042
♪ You could love and adore

29:13.042 --> 29:18.047
♪ Instead of a new

29:19.007 --> 29:21.718
♪ One last time

29:21.718 --> 29:25.680
♪ Just entre nous

29:25.680 --> 29:30.560
♪ Forgive me, then,
please try and trust me ♪

29:31.895 --> 29:36.900
♪ And I promise
not to disgust me ♪

29:38.401 --> 29:42.697
♪ You and me will
just adjust me ♪

29:44.073 --> 29:48.536
♪ And the 15th time will
be a different thing ♪

29:49.913 --> 29:54.584
♪ The 15th time will
be a different thing ♪

29:55.710 --> 29:59.714
♪ The 15th time will be

29:59.714 --> 30:01.925
♪ A different thing

30:01.925 --> 30:05.595
(slow piano music continues)

30:15.605 --> 30:16.564
I'm sorry.

30:20.610 --> 30:21.611
It's okay.

30:27.742 --> 30:28.952
[Michael] Is that for me?

30:30.453 --> 30:31.120
Maybe.

30:35.959 --> 30:37.627
(Laura laughs)

30:37.627 --> 30:38.795
Go sit down, I'll
get you dinner.

30:41.130 --> 30:42.632
[Dennis] Kiki!

30:45.593 --> 30:46.803
[Jan] Kiki!

30:46.803 --> 30:48.805
[Dennis] Kiki!

30:48.805 --> 30:49.806
You kids stay with the bus.

30:49.806 --> 30:50.974
[Jan] Kiki?

30:52.141 --> 30:53.309
Kiki!

30:53.309 --> 30:54.644
[Dennis] Jan, you all right?

30:54.644 --> 30:55.979
[Jan] We can't find Kiki!

30:55.979 --> 30:57.146
[Dennis] What?

31:12.328 --> 31:14.998
(Jan trembles)

31:18.167 --> 31:22.964
- [Jan] She's under, she's
under here, help me, help me!

31:31.848 --> 31:35.685
- Oh, it's just something
from Mother and Dad.

31:39.188 --> 31:41.024
They're just trying
to help, Mike.

32:15.016 --> 32:17.894
(Michael sighs)

32:17.894 --> 32:19.854
I'm not believing this.

32:19.854 --> 32:21.689
[Laura] What?

32:21.689 --> 32:23.566
- You remember Gary Culver
from medical school?

32:23.566 --> 32:26.069
He's teaching medicine
at a university here.

32:26.069 --> 32:29.238
He's teaching medicine,
he could barely spell it.

32:31.908 --> 32:33.743
- Isn't he the guy
that you brought up

32:33.743 --> 32:35.244
to Boston to hear me play?

32:35.244 --> 32:37.038
- Yeah, and he wants
me to come and lecture

32:37.038 --> 32:40.583
to his class about
emergency medicine. (laughs)

32:41.709 --> 32:42.919
That's great.

32:44.754 --> 32:47.715
Maybe he could help you get
back into medical school.

32:47.715 --> 32:50.426
- I don't need Gary Culvert to
get back into medical school.

32:52.762 --> 32:55.431
- Um, I just mean
scholarships and things.

32:55.431 --> 32:57.100
I know what that's all about.

32:57.100 --> 32:59.602
I ran rings around
him in medical school.

32:59.602 --> 33:01.229
I had to tutor
him on every exam.

33:04.107 --> 33:08.778
Now he's a doctor, he's a big
deal professor of medicine,

33:08.778 --> 33:09.779
and what am I, huh?

33:10.780 --> 33:12.782
Just an ambulance driver,

33:12.782 --> 33:14.117
if it was up to
them, Jesus Christ.

33:14.117 --> 33:16.285
- You're a
physician's assistant.

33:16.285 --> 33:18.413
Maybe he respects you, do
you ever think of that?

33:18.413 --> 33:20.248
Oh, honey, please.

33:20.248 --> 33:22.125
You know that no medical school

33:22.125 --> 33:24.127
in the world would
have a PA like me talk

33:24.127 --> 33:28.297
to a medical class about
emergency medicine.

33:31.467 --> 33:33.636
- Well, it just seems
like a good opportunity.

33:34.971 --> 33:36.931
I thought when you took
this job at the clinic

33:36.931 --> 33:39.100
that you'd be working your
way back into medical school.

33:39.100 --> 33:40.643
Hey, listen, you know,

33:40.643 --> 33:42.145
no more about medical
school, all right?

33:42.145 --> 33:45.314
First McCafferty, then
you and, uh. (laughs)

33:49.152 --> 33:52.655
- Well, I think we
need to talk about it.

33:54.323 --> 33:56.659
- Well, maybe I don't want
to go to medical school.

33:56.659 --> 33:57.827
You ever think of that?

33:59.162 --> 34:00.663
Maybe I want to
do something else.

34:02.123 --> 34:05.001
Earl has an idea, you
know, he's got an idea.

34:05.001 --> 34:06.961
Maybe it's good, I don't know.

34:09.338 --> 34:11.340
What idea?

34:11.340 --> 34:15.845
- Well, what's the number
one industry in this area?

34:16.846 --> 34:18.306
It's tourism, people come here,

34:18.306 --> 34:20.349
they want to fish and
they want to hunt,

34:20.349 --> 34:22.310
they want to enjoy the mountains

34:22.310 --> 34:25.521
and the trees and the lakes and
they can't get there by car.

34:27.190 --> 34:29.859
Now what if there's an outfit
that can fly them there?

34:29.859 --> 34:33.863
See, Earl has the experience,
I'm getting my license.

34:33.863 --> 34:36.032
We get a few thousand
dollars together,

34:36.032 --> 34:39.035
buy some pontoon skis for
the plane, we'll be all set.

34:41.037 --> 34:42.872
You know, we just
build a reputation,

34:42.872 --> 34:44.040
and then we'll
have more business

34:44.040 --> 34:45.208
than we know how to handle.

34:46.375 --> 34:48.044
It's an incredible opportunity.

34:49.837 --> 34:50.546
What do you think?

34:52.882 --> 34:54.842
(Laura scoffs)

34:54.842 --> 34:57.011
You can't be serious.

34:57.011 --> 34:58.554
[Michael] Why not?

35:01.390 --> 35:03.893
Well, Earl I can understand.

35:03.893 --> 35:05.853
He's got nothing better
to do than sit around,

35:05.853 --> 35:08.064
drink beer, and tell stupid
stories about his ex-wife

35:08.064 --> 35:09.899
and his Navy pilot days.

35:11.901 --> 35:16.739
But Mike, you could be
anything you want to be.

35:16.739 --> 35:18.741
You could be a
doctor, you could be-

35:18.741 --> 35:20.368
I'm doing the best I can!

35:23.913 --> 35:27.041
(silverware clanking)

35:44.392 --> 35:46.435
- I want us to go back
to New York, Mike.

35:48.396 --> 35:51.440
(Michael sighs)

35:51.440 --> 35:53.943
- Laura, we've talked
about this before.

35:53.943 --> 35:55.444
We are not going
back to New York.

35:57.947 --> 36:01.576
- I may not ever be able
to play well enough again

36:01.576 --> 36:06.289
to have a career, but (sighs)

36:06.289 --> 36:08.124
I'm ready to go back to work.

36:09.458 --> 36:13.129
I miss it, I miss all
of it, the practice,

36:13.129 --> 36:14.589
the dedication, the-

36:14.589 --> 36:16.299
- Hold on, you
can practice here,

36:16.299 --> 36:18.259
and we've got a
wonderful life here.

36:18.259 --> 36:19.927
We ski, we hike-

36:19.927 --> 36:21.929
- I don't want to do
it, I'm sick of it!

36:21.929 --> 36:24.807
I feel cut off, isolated.

36:24.807 --> 36:27.310
I want to go back,
I want to audition

36:27.310 --> 36:28.811
for the Chamber Orchestra again-

36:28.811 --> 36:30.938
Fine, audition anywhere,

36:30.938 --> 36:32.607
but we're not going
back to New York!

36:34.650 --> 36:36.485
- When are we gonna
stop running away?

36:39.322 --> 36:40.990
Ever since Jamie died-

36:40.990 --> 36:42.491
- No, don't, stop
it right there.

36:42.491 --> 36:44.160
(slow violin music)

36:44.160 --> 36:47.163
I've told you, just
don't bring that up.

36:47.163 --> 36:50.124
Everything's going along fine,
and you gotta bring this up.

36:52.001 --> 36:53.502
You know, you just
don't understand.

36:53.502 --> 36:55.171
You will never,
never understand.

36:56.631 --> 36:59.842
- No, you're the one
who won't let go!

36:59.842 --> 37:02.345
You have to stop
blaming yourself.

37:02.345 --> 37:06.182
(slow violin music continues)

37:11.187 --> 37:12.521
Mike, come back.

37:13.522 --> 37:15.483
I am sick of chasing after you!

37:18.527 --> 37:19.528
Then stop chasing.

37:20.696 --> 37:24.367
(slow violin music continues)

37:35.378 --> 37:40.174
(people shouting)
(slow orchestral music)

37:40.174 --> 37:41.384
[Group] Push!

37:43.552 --> 37:47.682
(slow orchestral
music continues)

37:59.402 --> 38:01.570
(Jan cries)

38:02.571 --> 38:05.241
(wind whistles)

38:11.414 --> 38:14.083
(siren wails)

38:18.921 --> 38:21.924
(slow violin music)

38:34.437 --> 38:37.732
(slow orchestral music)

38:57.626 --> 39:00.129
- [Jan] Five one thousand,
one one thousand,

39:00.129 --> 39:02.965
two one thousand,
three one thousand,

39:02.965 --> 39:05.468
four one thousand,
five one thousand.

39:05.468 --> 39:09.472
(quiet overlapping chattering)

39:11.640 --> 39:14.143
(slow orchestral
music continues)

39:14.143 --> 39:15.478
Okay, start CPR.

39:18.314 --> 39:20.107
We've got a pulse, Earl!

39:20.107 --> 39:24.153
(slow orchestral
music continues)

39:34.330 --> 39:35.664
Is anyone else injured?

39:35.664 --> 39:37.458
[Jan] No, we're all right.

39:37.458 --> 39:40.669
- She was under the car,
we couldn't get her out.

39:41.670 --> 39:43.172
[Michael] Are you all right?

39:43.172 --> 39:44.131
It's okay.

39:46.008 --> 39:50.346
- Okay, I need, I need
one person on each corner, all right?

39:51.347 --> 39:53.182
At least four people.

39:53.182 --> 39:56.519
Now, pick that oxygen up and
bring it up with me, all right?

39:56.519 --> 40:00.147
Now, one, two, three, lift.

40:00.147 --> 40:02.024
Easy, easy, all right.

40:05.361 --> 40:06.195
Okay.

40:08.531 --> 40:10.032
Easy.

40:10.032 --> 40:14.203
(slow orchestral
music continues)

40:22.545 --> 40:25.506
(slow piano music)

40:35.724 --> 40:38.727
(slow orchestral music)

40:38.727 --> 40:41.397
- I still can't believe
they found me under the car.

40:41.397 --> 40:42.398
And alive.

40:45.192 --> 40:47.403
Mom said it was a miracle.

40:47.403 --> 40:49.572
Michael thought so, too.

40:49.572 --> 40:50.531
And you?

40:53.242 --> 40:54.410
- Oh, I do, but-

40:56.745 --> 40:57.746
But what?

40:59.874 --> 41:03.252
- Well, sometimes miracles
just don't end up the way

41:03.252 --> 41:04.712
you think they will.

41:06.714 --> 41:09.383
- Then why do they
call them miracles?

41:10.759 --> 41:15.723
- Well, because they're
rare and beautiful,

41:17.558 --> 41:21.770
but we're stubborn and we
go back to our old ways

41:21.770 --> 41:23.772
and we forget what the purpose

41:23.772 --> 41:25.774
of the miracle was
in the first place.

41:28.611 --> 41:33.115
What was the purpose of mine?

41:33.115 --> 41:34.783
I'm not sure.

41:34.783 --> 41:37.786
There was a time I
was sure, but now,

41:40.456 --> 41:41.290
I'm not so sure.

41:45.586 --> 41:46.629
Me neither.

41:47.796 --> 41:51.800
(slow orchestral
music continues)

41:53.302 --> 41:56.263
- I wonder if I should
have left Michael.

42:02.770 --> 42:04.313
Why didn't you?

42:06.148 --> 42:06.815
I suppose

42:09.443 --> 42:13.822
'cause I loved him.
(slow piano music)

42:13.822 --> 42:15.324
Isn't that always the answer?

42:22.831 --> 42:26.835
Kiki, dear, do you know why
your father left your mother?

42:28.504 --> 42:29.338
Yes.

42:30.506 --> 42:31.674
[Laura] Then why was that?

42:35.511 --> 42:37.805
I don't know if I should,

42:39.348 --> 42:41.850
unless, if-

42:41.850 --> 42:42.685
Unless I know?

42:44.186 --> 42:44.853
Yes.

42:46.522 --> 42:47.356
I know.

42:48.357 --> 42:49.024
You do?

42:57.324 --> 43:01.829
- When you've lost
something dear to you,

43:03.539 --> 43:05.874
it becomes like an
unwelcome friend,

43:07.668 --> 43:09.878
and you can always sense when
it's coming around again.

43:14.717 --> 43:17.386
(siren wails)

43:29.023 --> 43:30.024
[Michael] How old is she?

43:30.024 --> 43:30.899
Six.

43:32.860 --> 43:34.403
- [Michael] Keep it
on the road, Earl!

43:34.403 --> 43:35.237
Kiki.

43:36.572 --> 43:38.407
Oh.

43:38.407 --> 43:40.242
(dramatic orchestral music)

43:40.242 --> 43:42.244
- [Earl] Unit two to base,
unit two to base, over.

43:42.244 --> 43:46.749
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

43:46.749 --> 43:49.418
Come on, McCafferty, come on.

43:49.418 --> 43:50.878
What happened?

43:50.878 --> 43:55.758
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

43:55.758 --> 43:57.593
(Dr. McCafferty mumbles)

43:57.593 --> 43:59.261
- [Earl] You're
on the box, Mike.

44:04.266 --> 44:06.894
Look, doc, yeah, we got a, uh,

44:06.894 --> 44:08.937
six-year-old female,
condition critical,

44:08.937 --> 44:10.898
blunt trauma to the
neck, possibly chest,

44:10.898 --> 44:12.941
probable with head injury,

44:12.941 --> 44:15.778
and unconscious without
spontaneous respiration.

44:15.778 --> 44:17.946
Unequal pupils,
disheveled posturing,

44:17.946 --> 44:20.449
and a possible
intracerebral edema

44:20.449 --> 44:22.951
and a possible hemathorax, over.

44:24.578 --> 44:26.455
- [Dr. McCafferty]
What do you think?

44:26.455 --> 44:27.790
- She's got a pronounced
(indistinct) edema, doctor.

44:27.790 --> 44:29.625
I've given her
Maltitol and Decadron,

44:29.625 --> 44:31.585
and her hypothermia's
what's keeping her going,

44:31.585 --> 44:32.961
but if it reverses, we've
got out hands full, over.

44:32.961 --> 44:35.422
(background noise
drowns out speaker)

44:35.422 --> 44:37.132
- [Dr. McCafferty] I'm
trusting your judgment, doctor.

44:37.132 --> 44:39.468
- I'm pushing down
her now at half a gram

44:39.468 --> 44:41.303
and I can't catch it.

44:41.303 --> 44:44.807
- [Dr. McCafferty] All right,
(indistinct), but slowly.

44:44.807 --> 44:47.976
- I'd like to use some Valium
in one milligram doses, over.

44:47.976 --> 44:50.104
- [Dr. McCafferty]
Okay, go ahead.

44:50.104 --> 44:52.815
- What's happening,
why doesn't it stop?

44:52.815 --> 44:57.486
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

44:59.988 --> 45:01.490
- [Michael] Now
keep that steady.

45:02.825 --> 45:06.829
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

45:26.473 --> 45:27.683
- [Dr. McCafferty] Get
her on the respirator

45:27.683 --> 45:29.518
and the cardiac monitor.

45:29.518 --> 45:32.020
I need test films, head and
neck, and blood gadgets, stat.

45:34.648 --> 45:39.528
(phone rings)
(machinery beeps)

45:44.032 --> 45:46.034
Don't go too far,
Dietrich, I may need you.

45:47.035 --> 45:47.870
Excuse me.

45:50.038 --> 45:51.206
How are you doing?

45:51.206 --> 45:53.041
I need to call my husband.

45:53.041 --> 45:54.877
He works at Clearwater
Airport, I'm sure

45:54.877 --> 45:56.545
- you could get someone-
- Clearwater, yeah,

45:56.545 --> 45:58.172
I know Clearwater,
I fly up there.

45:58.172 --> 45:59.047
Who's your husband?

45:59.047 --> 46:00.174
Chuck Scott.

46:00.174 --> 46:02.050
You're Chuck Scott's wife?

46:02.050 --> 46:04.678
Well, when Dr. McCafferty gets
your little girl stabilized,

46:04.678 --> 46:06.555
we're gonna fly her out of here.

46:06.555 --> 46:09.016
We're gonna take her to
the Regional Trauma Center

46:09.016 --> 46:10.893
and Chuck can meet
us there, okay?

46:10.893 --> 46:12.561
Okay.

46:12.561 --> 46:14.062
- Now, they've got the
best diagnostic tools

46:14.062 --> 46:17.566
in the whole country and
one of the best staffs,

46:17.566 --> 46:19.693
so you call him right there,
the phone's over there

46:19.693 --> 46:21.570
- in the office.
- Okay.

46:21.570 --> 46:23.405
- All right, and tell him
we're doing everything we can.

46:24.406 --> 46:25.407
Thanks.

46:25.407 --> 46:27.910
(machinery beeps)

46:34.082 --> 46:35.918
- It's hard to tell
without a CT scan

46:35.918 --> 46:38.420
and an EEG the amount of
brain damage she's suffered,

46:39.755 --> 46:41.256
but you did a nice
job, Dietrich,

46:43.091 --> 46:45.761
getting the edema and the
seizures under control.

46:47.095 --> 46:48.263
She's got a chance.

46:53.060 --> 46:54.728
(monitor flatlines)

46:54.728 --> 46:55.938
Code blue, we got
a cardiac arrest.

46:55.938 --> 46:58.774
(dramatic orchestral music)

46:58.774 --> 47:00.609
Let Dietrich do that.

47:00.609 --> 47:04.947
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

47:06.949 --> 47:07.783
Clear.

47:15.582 --> 47:16.959
Is she all right?

47:16.959 --> 47:18.794
- [Dr. McCafferty]
Kids, get out of here.

47:18.794 --> 47:23.632
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

47:23.632 --> 47:25.968
Repeat the (indistinct).

47:25.968 --> 47:30.597
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

47:38.814 --> 47:39.648
Clear.

47:40.983 --> 47:45.612
(dramatic orchestral
music continues)

47:51.827 --> 47:54.663
- God, please
don't let Kiki die.

47:57.833 --> 47:58.667
Clear.

48:02.004 --> 48:04.840
(machinery beeps)

48:14.850 --> 48:18.020
Earl, call the medevac guys,
tell them to get here stat.

48:18.020 --> 48:21.356
(slow orchestral music)

48:31.700 --> 48:33.869
What are you doing here?

48:33.869 --> 48:35.329
I've made a decision.

48:35.329 --> 48:36.705
I'm going to my
sister's in New York.

48:39.041 --> 48:40.208
Right now?

48:40.208 --> 48:42.044
Well, I'm catching the shuttle

48:42.044 --> 48:44.713
into the city for a
nine o'clock flight.

48:44.713 --> 48:46.006
I'm leaving, Mike.

48:47.549 --> 48:50.344
- Oh, Laura, please-

48:50.344 --> 48:52.721
- Look, you say you're
happy here, I'm not.

48:56.391 --> 48:58.060
I can't talk right now.

48:59.561 --> 49:01.229
Wait until I get back.

49:01.229 --> 49:03.231
- [Earl] Mike, come
on, we're ready to go.

49:04.858 --> 49:06.026
Okay.

49:06.026 --> 49:08.362
What's going on here?

49:08.362 --> 49:11.073
- We've got a patient,
a little girl.

49:11.073 --> 49:12.908
There's not much hope,

49:12.908 --> 49:15.243
but we're gonna move her
to the trauma center.

49:15.243 --> 49:16.745
- [Dr. McCafferty]
Let's go, Dietrich.

49:16.745 --> 49:21.083
- Okay, wait 'til I get
back and we'll talk.

49:23.251 --> 49:24.086
Please.

49:27.089 --> 49:28.715
- You're going with
her, aren't you?

49:28.715 --> 49:29.925
You've gotta go with her.

49:29.925 --> 49:33.220
(slow orchestral music)

50:06.962 --> 50:11.091
(airplane engine roars)

50:11.091 --> 50:15.137
(slow orchestral
music continues)

50:40.328 --> 50:42.164
How you doing?

50:42.164 --> 50:45.167
- I'm trying to convince
myself this isn't all my fault.

50:46.835 --> 50:49.838
- Keep trying, these
things, they just happen.

50:49.838 --> 50:53.175
I know, but why Kiki?

50:53.175 --> 50:55.343
She's such a sweet little girl.

50:57.179 --> 51:00.015
- It's not your fault, the
roads are terrible now.

51:00.015 --> 51:02.017
- My husband told me
to wait another day.

51:02.017 --> 51:03.351
I should have listened.

51:05.020 --> 51:06.980
Well, that won't help any.

51:06.980 --> 51:09.191
Believe me, I've been down
that road a million times.

51:10.817 --> 51:12.194
It's all I can think about.

51:18.533 --> 51:19.868
Do you have any children?

51:24.873 --> 51:26.708
I had a son.

51:28.877 --> 51:30.378
He was two,

51:30.378 --> 51:33.840
and there was an
accident, a fall

51:35.884 --> 51:37.552
down the stairs
of our brownstone.

51:39.054 --> 51:42.057
You know, a day doesn't
go by when I don't think

51:42.057 --> 51:44.059
of what I could have
done differently then.

51:48.563 --> 51:50.398
(Michael sighs)

51:50.398 --> 51:52.234
But it won't bring him back.

51:56.238 --> 51:59.241
I'm so sorry. (cries)

51:59.241 --> 52:01.201
- So don't blame
yourself, you know,

52:01.201 --> 52:02.536
Kiki wouldn't want that.

52:05.080 --> 52:08.083
- She'd be more concerned
about me than I am of her.

52:09.417 --> 52:11.753
- Yeah, that's a
way to look at it.

52:11.753 --> 52:13.255
All right, there you go,

52:13.255 --> 52:15.257
think about what Kiki
would say to you.

52:17.259 --> 52:19.094
- What would your
son say to you?

52:25.267 --> 52:27.435
- Well, you know, he
was something, he'd say,

52:34.067 --> 52:37.946
you know kids, they come
out with things, and...

52:46.955 --> 52:48.957
- [Jan] What would
you say to him?

52:52.294 --> 52:53.795
Oh, that's easy, I,

52:55.964 --> 52:58.300
I'd say "I love you" about
a million times, (cries)

52:58.300 --> 53:02.304
and I'd say, "I'm sorry,
I'm sorry, I'm sorry,"

53:02.304 --> 53:07.309
and maybe he could believe
me, you know? (cries)

53:08.476 --> 53:09.811
I know he'd believe you.

53:15.442 --> 53:18.987
Will you stay with
Kiki when we get there?

53:21.281 --> 53:22.824
(Michael sighs)

53:22.824 --> 53:23.825
- Well, you know, they
got the best doctors

53:23.825 --> 53:25.327
in the country there,

53:25.327 --> 53:26.328
so there's nothing for
you to worry about.

53:26.328 --> 53:29.998
[Jan] Will you?

53:29.998 --> 53:30.832
I...

53:39.341 --> 53:41.176
Yes, of course I will.

53:49.643 --> 53:53.355
- We all know Kiki's in bad
shape, she needs our help.

53:57.025 --> 53:58.360
Let's all pray for Kiki.

54:13.208 --> 54:16.169
(airplane engine roars)

54:16.169 --> 54:20.048
- It's very weak, but she's
breathing on her own now.

54:21.216 --> 54:24.386
(slow orchestral music)

54:51.413 --> 54:54.082
(traffic roars)

55:01.548 --> 55:02.590
[Chuck] Kiki Scott.

55:08.054 --> 55:09.431
- [Announcer] Dr. Davis,
telephone, please.

55:09.431 --> 55:11.599
Dr. Davis, telephone, please.

55:20.275 --> 55:22.277
- This is Dr. Leighton at
the Regional Trauma Center.

55:22.277 --> 55:23.778
Let me speak to Dr. McCafferty.

55:25.947 --> 55:27.615
Hello, Mac, how are you?

55:27.615 --> 55:31.286
I need some information,
this Scott girl you sent us.

55:31.286 --> 55:33.121
- [Dr. McCafferty]
She didn't make it?

55:33.121 --> 55:36.082
- She made it through, in fact,
she's considerably improved.

55:36.082 --> 55:38.460
That's what I wanted
to ask you about.

55:38.460 --> 55:41.629
Her CT scan's negative,
no focus of bleeding,

55:41.629 --> 55:43.757
only a cerebral edema.

55:43.757 --> 55:45.592
There's a pneumothorax
in the left chest,

55:45.592 --> 55:47.969
but that was taken care
of by the chest tube.

55:49.304 --> 55:50.638
Mac, this girl's
going to be fine.

55:50.638 --> 55:52.307
What do you mean fine?

55:53.475 --> 55:54.642
So she's out of the coma?

55:54.642 --> 55:55.977
[Dr. Leighton] Yes.

55:55.977 --> 55:56.978
She's breathing voluntarily?

55:56.978 --> 55:58.646
[Dr. Leighton] Yes.

55:58.646 --> 56:01.107
- What about the seizures,
the cardiac arrest?

56:01.107 --> 56:01.983
[Dr. Leighton] Nothing.

56:03.443 --> 56:05.111
- [Dr. McCafferty]
It's not possible.

56:12.494 --> 56:13.828
- [Dennis] She's
gonna be all right!

56:13.828 --> 56:17.123
(group cheers)

56:17.123 --> 56:18.500
(Dr. McCafferty laughs)

56:18.500 --> 56:21.669
- I don't believe it, I
just don't believe it.

56:25.173 --> 56:28.843
Gelling, I'm sorry,
what is it again?

56:28.843 --> 56:30.637
- Would you go over your
records with me again?

56:30.637 --> 56:32.180
We must be missing something.

56:42.190 --> 56:43.817
[Chuck] Perfect landing, sir.

56:43.817 --> 56:45.360
She'll be all right?

56:45.360 --> 56:47.362
- She's fine, she's
a little beat up,

56:47.362 --> 56:50.657
but no brain damage,
no spinal cord damage.

56:50.657 --> 56:52.534
I think she's
gonna be just fine.

56:54.202 --> 56:55.203
Well, how about that?

56:55.203 --> 56:56.371
Yeah.

56:56.371 --> 56:57.497
(group laughs)

56:57.497 --> 56:58.373
Thanks.

57:00.375 --> 57:02.377
I can't begin to tell you.

57:02.377 --> 57:03.878
She's quite a little girl.

57:03.878 --> 57:05.672
[Jan] You saved her life.

57:05.672 --> 57:06.881
Can I go in and see her?

57:06.881 --> 57:07.882
- Sure.
- Oh.

57:13.179 --> 57:16.057
(slow piano music)

57:21.563 --> 57:26.568
(slow violin music)
(slow piano music)

58:21.247 --> 58:24.292
- On that airplane, when
they were taking you

58:24.292 --> 58:27.128
to St. Joe's,
something happened.

58:28.796 --> 58:32.467
It was, it was as if when you
started breathing on your own,

58:32.467 --> 58:34.469
Michael started breathing again.

58:37.305 --> 58:41.768
After years of blaming
and crucifying himself,

58:41.768 --> 58:44.812
he was finally able to

58:46.648 --> 58:51.653
make peace about the loss
of our precious little boy.

58:54.322 --> 58:56.658
- That must have been
really hard on you two.

58:56.658 --> 58:57.951
Oh, it was.

59:00.995 --> 59:02.497
It was hard enough
to lose Jamie,

59:02.497 --> 59:04.499
but then to lose
Michael, too, it was-

59:06.793 --> 59:10.838
- Mother used to say
when, when he saved me,

59:12.632 --> 59:13.508
he saved himself.

59:16.511 --> 59:18.513
No, she would know, I guess.

59:21.474 --> 59:25.353
Something else happened on
that plane, they bonded,

59:26.854 --> 59:30.316
emotionally in a way that

59:32.694 --> 59:33.987
it's hard to understand.

59:36.364 --> 59:37.532
When did you find out?

59:41.703 --> 59:45.540
- After so many years
of marriage, you,

59:47.375 --> 59:49.711
if you're awake, you
know these things,

59:49.711 --> 59:50.837
at least we women do.

59:54.382 --> 59:58.344
I just knew I was
losing Michael again.

01:00:03.891 --> 01:00:05.393
When did you find out?

01:00:07.061 --> 01:00:07.895
Mother told me.

01:00:10.398 --> 01:00:15.403
- That was honest
of her. (laughs)

01:00:17.071 --> 01:00:21.576
- Alan was on tour, my
mother came over for dinner.

01:00:22.910 --> 01:00:24.746
She brought over her
famous apple dumplings.

01:00:27.540 --> 01:00:32.378
We went and cleaned
the kitchen, and

01:00:32.378 --> 01:00:34.922
we went to the dining table, and

01:00:38.092 --> 01:00:39.552
poured some tea.

01:00:42.430 --> 01:00:44.724
And then she grabbed my hand

01:00:46.267 --> 01:00:48.770
and kept saying
that she was sorry,

01:00:48.770 --> 01:00:52.607
she was sorry, sorry, and I
was like, "For what, like?"

01:00:54.442 --> 01:00:58.613
And then she told me that
she was leaving my father.

01:01:05.953 --> 01:01:06.788
And then

01:01:07.955 --> 01:01:08.790
she said,

01:01:11.918 --> 01:01:12.919
she said-

01:01:13.795 --> 01:01:14.629
She said what?

01:01:16.464 --> 01:01:19.300
- She said that she was
in love with another man,

01:01:21.469 --> 01:01:25.973
that she was in love
with Michael. (cries)

01:01:25.973 --> 01:01:27.141
I was sorry.

01:01:30.311 --> 01:01:31.646
You didn't know, did you?

01:01:32.814 --> 01:01:35.817
I did, sweetie, in my heart.

01:01:35.817 --> 01:01:39.153
(slow orchestral music)

01:01:40.822 --> 01:01:44.325
It's not your fault,
(cries) it's not your fault.

01:01:44.325 --> 01:01:45.827
It's not your fault.

01:01:45.827 --> 01:01:47.662
- But it is my fault, I
feel like it's my fault

01:01:47.662 --> 01:01:51.499
because it's like, I just
worshiped this man, you know,

01:01:51.499 --> 01:01:52.625
the man that saved me.

01:01:54.001 --> 01:01:55.503
I mean, you guys used
to come over and visit,

01:01:55.503 --> 01:01:58.131
and we'd had so much fun.

01:02:00.007 --> 01:02:02.844
I just thought that we were
gonna be friends forever.

01:02:04.011 --> 01:02:04.971
Look.

01:02:06.681 --> 01:02:08.683
If it was anybody's
fault, it was mine.

01:02:10.476 --> 01:02:13.020
We'd been planning on
visiting you for months,

01:02:13.020 --> 01:02:16.524
and then I got the offer from
the orchestra to do the solo,

01:02:16.524 --> 01:02:19.819
and it was a piece
I'd auditioned with 30 years earlier,

01:02:19.819 --> 01:02:24.699
and Michael, Michael
seemed to understand.

01:02:26.200 --> 01:02:28.870
He said, "Stay,
darling, you have to.

01:02:30.538 --> 01:02:32.540
I'll be fine, fine."

01:02:34.542 --> 01:02:35.710
He wasn't fine.

01:02:37.044 --> 01:02:41.007
It was always something in him,

01:02:41.007 --> 01:02:44.385
something that I
could never quiet.

01:02:46.721 --> 01:02:51.726
We could never have another
child, and he just threw himself

01:02:53.227 --> 01:02:55.229
into his work at the
hospital, and I with my music,

01:02:55.229 --> 01:02:58.566
and we just grew further
and further apart.

01:03:05.573 --> 01:03:10.077
If I had to do it all over
again, I'd do it just the same.

01:03:11.746 --> 01:03:13.706
But I should have
gone that week.

01:03:15.041 --> 01:03:16.417
None of this would
have happened.

01:03:18.586 --> 01:03:20.087
You can't blame yourself.

01:03:23.090 --> 01:03:24.550
Nor can you.

01:03:25.760 --> 01:03:29.931
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:03:46.572 --> 01:03:48.115
- Did Michael ever know that-

01:03:48.115 --> 01:03:49.075
That I knew?

01:03:51.744 --> 01:03:52.620
No.

01:03:54.622 --> 01:03:56.749
Some things are
better left unsaid.

01:03:59.085 --> 01:04:01.629
He got sick soon
after coming home,

01:04:01.629 --> 01:04:06.634
and any plans he had of
leaving me were soon gone.

01:04:10.137 --> 01:04:11.806
And I knew he was here to stay.

01:04:13.307 --> 01:04:17.645
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:04:18.813 --> 01:04:22.316
(airplane engine rattles)

01:04:24.652 --> 01:04:28.781
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:05:05.192 --> 01:05:07.320
- [Earl] Old McCafferty
didn't do a bad job

01:05:07.320 --> 01:05:09.864
for an old horse doctor, did he?

01:05:09.864 --> 01:05:11.157
[Michael] What time is it?

01:05:12.199 --> 01:05:14.035
[Earl] It's about four.

01:05:15.661 --> 01:05:16.871
Are you gonna go
home and sack up?

01:05:18.873 --> 01:05:20.207
[Michael] Yeah, I guess so.

01:05:21.709 --> 01:05:22.668
I don't know why.

01:05:27.715 --> 01:05:30.885
- Well, you're a lot better
off without her, believe me.

01:05:32.678 --> 01:05:36.015
You may not think so now,
but, hey, let her go.

01:05:38.225 --> 01:05:41.896
I remember when me and
old Carmelita broke up.

01:05:41.896 --> 01:05:46.233
I was 7,000 miles away
on an aircraft carrier

01:05:46.233 --> 01:05:49.570
with three months of
duty in front of me.

01:05:51.238 --> 01:05:55.076
I was so low, I didn't care
about nothing, except flying

01:05:56.577 --> 01:05:58.913
and way too much
John Barleycorn.

01:06:02.750 --> 01:06:05.252
We just have to get you
back up where you belong.

01:06:06.921 --> 01:06:07.922
You'll be okay.

01:06:34.407 --> 01:06:36.117
- [Michael] Don't
you have a home?

01:06:38.285 --> 01:06:41.622
- You know, that was really
fine work you did last night.

01:06:46.127 --> 01:06:47.962
She's a very lucky girl.

01:06:48.963 --> 01:06:50.131
[Dr. McCafferty] Lucky to have

01:06:50.131 --> 01:06:51.424
first rate medical attention.

01:06:54.635 --> 01:06:56.303
- But I didn't do
anything special.

01:06:57.930 --> 01:07:00.474
- A good doctor never
does anything special,

01:07:01.642 --> 01:07:03.144
he does everything he can.

01:07:04.478 --> 01:07:06.772
You were there, you
knew what to do.

01:07:06.772 --> 01:07:08.816
- But that doesn't
explain what happened.

01:07:11.152 --> 01:07:15.156
Now, you look at this file,
and you tell me what happened,

01:07:16.991 --> 01:07:20.161
because I was there and I
don't know what happened.

01:07:23.998 --> 01:07:27.126
- All right, you
need an explanation.

01:07:28.502 --> 01:07:30.671
Let's see if I can
find you one or two.

01:07:32.465 --> 01:07:34.341
How about the snow cushioned her

01:07:34.341 --> 01:07:37.011
so she didn't suffer
any cervical damage

01:07:37.011 --> 01:07:40.014
or broken ribs, therefore
no internal bleeding.

01:07:42.016 --> 01:07:46.020
Or how about, um, her
hypothermia slowed her metabolic rate,

01:07:47.021 --> 01:07:49.023
reduced her need for oxygen,

01:07:49.023 --> 01:07:53.861
she received CPR and the right
medicine at the right time,

01:07:53.861 --> 01:07:56.363
thus preventing
permanent brain damage

01:07:56.363 --> 01:07:58.866
from the intracranial edema.

01:08:00.493 --> 01:08:01.994
See how easy it is?

01:08:04.038 --> 01:08:05.873
I'm very impressed, Doctor.

01:08:12.713 --> 01:08:14.048
But that doesn't explain it.

01:08:15.883 --> 01:08:17.551
That doesn't explain
what happened.

01:08:19.011 --> 01:08:20.054
It doesn't, does it?

01:08:22.348 --> 01:08:23.349
No, it doesn't.

01:08:27.186 --> 01:08:28.395
You know, Dietrich,

01:08:30.856 --> 01:08:34.401
I believe after 30
years of practice,

01:08:36.237 --> 01:08:39.240
I've discovered that
doctors don't heal people.

01:08:40.908 --> 01:08:43.244
Now, we're there,
we participate,

01:08:45.412 --> 01:08:48.249
but it's not up to us
to make people whole.

01:08:51.252 --> 01:08:54.880
(Michael sighs)

01:08:54.880 --> 01:08:58.592
- If I left here, could
you get along without me?

01:08:59.885 --> 01:09:02.263
Oh, well, gee,

01:09:02.263 --> 01:09:07.101
yeah, I guess I could
manage somehow, Doctor.

01:09:10.938 --> 01:09:13.107
- You've got a little
shaving cream right here.

01:09:13.107 --> 01:09:14.441
Where, here?

01:09:14.441 --> 01:09:15.943
[Michael] No, right there.

01:09:15.943 --> 01:09:16.944
Here?

01:09:16.944 --> 01:09:17.444
[Michael] There we go.

01:09:17.444 --> 01:09:19.113
Oh.

01:09:19.113 --> 01:09:20.614
Thanks.

01:09:20.614 --> 01:09:22.283
Thank you, Doctor.

01:09:25.911 --> 01:09:29.123
(slow orchestral music)

01:09:35.921 --> 01:09:38.799
(car door slams)

01:09:38.799 --> 01:09:42.970
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:10:39.193 --> 01:10:43.364
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:11:24.405 --> 01:11:27.408
(slow piano music)

01:12:37.144 --> 01:12:40.981
(slow piano music continues)

01:13:36.537 --> 01:13:39.498
- Sorry I don't have any
dumplings to go with this.

01:13:39.498 --> 01:13:41.708
- Oh, (laughs)
you are so wicked.

01:13:43.544 --> 01:13:45.671
I swear, I will never eat
another apple dumpling

01:13:45.671 --> 01:13:46.547
as long as I live.

01:13:48.048 --> 01:13:50.717
(slow piano music)

01:13:57.724 --> 01:14:00.561
Have you ever been
able to forgive them?

01:14:04.731 --> 01:14:05.566
I think so.

01:14:08.527 --> 01:14:09.403
It's tough.

01:14:10.404 --> 01:14:12.406
Unfaithfulness has its own

01:14:14.575 --> 01:14:18.370
fears and jealousies,
it's never easy.

01:14:19.913 --> 01:14:23.250
Nothing quick about forgiveness,
especially for yourself,

01:14:24.251 --> 01:14:25.419
but I think I have.

01:14:27.254 --> 01:14:29.256
And you, have you forgiven them?

01:14:30.090 --> 01:14:30.757
No.

01:14:34.261 --> 01:14:36.263
I'm trying to work on it.

01:14:37.556 --> 01:14:40.893
I'm just really hurt. (cries)

01:14:42.728 --> 01:14:44.897
And that Mom, she finds
about Michael's sickness,

01:14:44.897 --> 01:14:47.274
and she does this complete 180,

01:14:47.274 --> 01:14:49.443
she's begging for my dad back.

01:14:49.443 --> 01:14:51.403
She's saying it's
good for the family.

01:14:52.613 --> 01:14:55.282
But he's not responding,
he's so hurt.

01:14:55.282 --> 01:14:56.783
He's never forgive her.

01:14:56.783 --> 01:15:00.621
Once he left, he's
never coming back.

01:15:02.122 --> 01:15:05.959
And then here I am,
counseling people

01:15:05.959 --> 01:15:10.631
on their relationships
and marriage and families,

01:15:10.631 --> 01:15:12.299
and then I look
at my own family,

01:15:12.299 --> 01:15:14.760
and they are so screwed up.

01:15:16.470 --> 01:15:19.973
And then Alan, he thinks I
come from this perfect family,

01:15:19.973 --> 01:15:22.309
and that we were great
and we went to church,

01:15:22.309 --> 01:15:24.811
and then he started
to go to church.

01:15:24.811 --> 01:15:27.147
And then he found
out what happened,

01:15:27.147 --> 01:15:29.608
and he just thought we
were a bunch of hypocrites.

01:15:31.652 --> 01:15:32.653
Are you worried?

01:15:34.321 --> 01:15:36.281
Yeah, I am.

01:15:37.783 --> 01:15:42.329
He's down under, he has
a number one single.

01:15:42.329 --> 01:15:44.665
Of course there's gonna
be groupies everywhere.

01:15:46.166 --> 01:15:48.502
I don't know, he wanted
me to come with him,

01:15:50.295 --> 01:15:52.673
but I didn't go, and
maybe I should have gone.

01:15:52.673 --> 01:15:54.508
Maybe.

01:15:54.508 --> 01:15:56.510
- But now I have this practice
and it's up and running

01:15:56.510 --> 01:15:58.679
and it's going really good.

01:16:00.847 --> 01:16:02.849
But then I have the
best therapist, and now she quit on me.

01:16:02.849 --> 01:16:04.518
Oh, no.

01:16:04.518 --> 01:16:05.852
- And I have to
take on her load.

01:16:07.354 --> 01:16:09.356
- Couldn't you just
Zoom her clients

01:16:09.356 --> 01:16:10.691
until you get a replacement?

01:16:11.858 --> 01:16:12.693
I suppose.

01:16:14.528 --> 01:16:15.696
Then go see him.

01:16:16.863 --> 01:16:17.864
I don't know.

01:16:17.864 --> 01:16:19.324
What, why not?

01:16:20.367 --> 01:16:21.868
Do you need money for a ticket?

01:16:21.868 --> 01:16:23.996
No, I'm good, thanks.

01:16:23.996 --> 01:16:26.373
Then go see him for a while.

01:16:26.373 --> 01:16:29.042
Tell him that you're gonna
keep your eye on him,

01:16:29.042 --> 01:16:32.546
and if he so much as touches
one of those groupies,

01:16:32.546 --> 01:16:35.549
he won't have a warm
bed to come home to.

01:16:35.549 --> 01:16:37.718
(Kiki laughs)

01:16:37.718 --> 01:16:41.388
I'm assuming the conjugal
bed is still warm?

01:16:41.388 --> 01:16:44.683
- Oh, we have no problems
in that situation. (laughs)

01:16:44.683 --> 01:16:48.395
- Oh, good, good,
then go call him.

01:16:48.395 --> 01:16:51.898
Tell him that you love
him, that he's your man,

01:16:53.400 --> 01:16:56.403
and, you know, you
guys have been in love

01:16:56.403 --> 01:16:58.905
since you were kids,
it's in your DNA.

01:17:01.742 --> 01:17:04.244
Don't let him go,
don't lose Alan.

01:17:07.247 --> 01:17:08.248
I want to call him.

01:17:08.248 --> 01:17:08.915
[Laura] Good.

01:17:08.915 --> 01:17:10.751
Yeah. (laughs)

01:17:10.751 --> 01:17:14.713
- Go in there, that is my
prayer, meditation, yoga room,

01:17:14.713 --> 01:17:17.382
sometimes screaming
weeping room,

01:17:17.382 --> 01:17:19.259
and you'll be private in there.

01:17:21.762 --> 01:17:24.765
[Kiki] Thank you, thank you.

01:17:24.765 --> 01:17:28.101
(slow orchestral music)

01:17:29.936 --> 01:17:30.896
I love you, Kiki.

01:17:35.776 --> 01:17:36.943
I love you too, Laura.

01:17:38.278 --> 01:17:42.407
(slow orchestral
music continues)

01:18:15.982 --> 01:18:18.819
So I lied to you, my darling.

01:18:22.155 --> 01:18:24.491
You'd be up there in
the air with crazy Earl,

01:18:24.491 --> 01:18:26.493
flying around for
hours at a time.

01:18:30.497 --> 01:18:34.000
I was lonely.
(slow piano music)

01:18:35.335 --> 01:18:36.837
Things had grown so cold.

01:18:39.673 --> 01:18:43.510
(slow piano music continues)

01:19:05.699 --> 01:19:10.704
I was so lonely, empty.
(slow piano music continues)

01:19:14.207 --> 01:19:18.044
And then Chuck would come over
just to say a friendly hi,

01:19:22.174 --> 01:19:24.050
and, uh, then things
got too friendly.

01:19:27.679 --> 01:19:28.722
I'm so sorry.

01:19:31.016 --> 01:19:32.726
I'm so sorry that I,

01:19:34.728 --> 01:19:37.564
that I couldn't love you
the way I was supposed to.

01:19:41.860 --> 01:19:43.069
Never make you happy.

01:19:46.573 --> 01:19:48.033
That's why I wanted to get away,

01:19:48.033 --> 01:19:49.743
it's why I wanted to
come back to New York.

01:19:49.743 --> 01:19:51.745
It's why I couldn't
stand going back there,

01:19:53.205 --> 01:19:54.706
knowing I'd betrayed you.

01:19:58.585 --> 01:20:01.588
(Laura sighs)

01:20:01.588 --> 01:20:04.925
I'm so sorry, sweet Michael.

01:20:07.928 --> 01:20:11.932
Forgive me, as
I've forgiven you.

01:20:18.772 --> 01:20:22.609
(slow piano music continues)

01:20:25.612 --> 01:20:28.615
(slow piano music)

01:20:45.465 --> 01:20:48.802
(slow orchestral music)

01:20:50.136 --> 01:20:52.472
♪ Sometimes things
come too fast ♪

01:20:52.472 --> 01:20:54.474
♪ I don't know what to do

01:20:54.474 --> 01:20:56.977
♪ How to act responsibly

01:20:56.977 --> 01:20:59.980
♪ Or how to see things through

01:20:59.980 --> 01:21:04.109
♪ But if I'd been around
earlier that way ♪

01:21:04.109 --> 01:21:06.820
♪ I could be quite reasonable

01:21:06.820 --> 01:21:11.658
♪ So hear me again while I say

01:21:11.658 --> 01:21:16.663
♪ Forgive me again
if I've offended ♪

01:21:18.123 --> 01:21:22.002
♪ And turned something
right into up and dead ♪

01:21:23.503 --> 01:21:27.507
♪ Muddled what
was comprehended ♪

01:21:27.507 --> 01:21:32.512
♪ But the 15th time will
be a different thing ♪

01:21:34.014 --> 01:21:38.685
♪ But the 15th time will
be a different thing ♪

01:21:39.853 --> 01:21:43.523
♪ But the 15th time will be

01:21:43.523 --> 01:21:46.526
♪ A different thing

01:21:57.871 --> 01:21:58.872
I'm sorry.

01:22:02.167 --> 01:22:03.168
It's okay.

01:22:05.545 --> 01:22:08.882
(slow orchestral music)
